Background
Modern logistics and inventory operations face growing pressure to deliver goods quickly, reduce transportation costs, and maintain accurate stock levels across warehouses and distribution points. However, many organizations still rely on manual planning or disconnected systems for route scheduling and inventory monitoring, which leads to inefficient deliveries, poor visibility, and slow decision-making.

In logistics operations, inefficient route planning can increase fuel consumption, delivery times, and operational costs, especially when traffic conditions, vehicle capacity, and multiple delivery locations are not considered properly. At the same time, poor inventory planning causes stockouts and overstocking, which can result in lost sales, tied-up capital, excess storage costs, and customer dissatisfaction.

Smart logistics systems have emerged as a solution to these challenges by combining route optimization, real-time tracking, and data-driven inventory management into a single platform. By using geographic data, live updates, and predictive analysis, such systems can improve operational efficiency, reduce waste, and support faster, more accurate logistics decisions.

Problem statement
Many small and medium-scale logistics and warehouse operations do not have an integrated system to optimize delivery routes and manage inventory efficiently in real time. As a result, vehicles often follow inefficient routes, fuel and transport costs increase, deliveries are delayed, and stock levels are not maintained accurately across locations.

In addition, the lack of proper demand forecasting and inventory visibility leads to frequent stockouts or overstock situations, both of which negatively affect profitability and service quality. Therefore, there is a need for a smart logistics and inventory optimization system that can support route planning, delivery monitoring, and predictive stock management in a unified solution.

Short academic version
Background: Logistics and inventory management are critical functions in supply chain operations, but traditional manual methods often lead to inefficient routing, higher transport costs, delayed deliveries, and inventory imbalance. Advances in smart logistics technologies such as real-time tracking, route optimization, and predictive inventory analysis provide opportunities to improve efficiency, reduce cost, and enhance service reliability.

Problem Statement: The absence of an integrated system for delivery route optimization and inventory control causes operational inefficiencies such as increased fuel usage, delayed deliveries, stockouts, overstocking, and poor visibility across warehouses and vehicles. This project proposes a Smart Logistics and Inventory Optimizer to address these issues through geospatial routing, real-time monitoring, and predictive inventory planning.